# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1796-united-states-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] The first midterm elections were held in the United States in 1790 and 1791.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] They occurred in the middle of President George Washington's first term, and determined the members of the 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Formal political parties did not exist, but Congress was broadly divided between a faction supporting the policies of the Washington administration and a faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Despite modest gains for the anti-administration faction, the pro-administration faction retained control of both houses of Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Vermont and Kentucky joined the union during the 2nd Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the House, neither faction made significant gains or losses, and the pro-administration faction retained control of the chamber.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the anti-administration faction picked up a moderate number of seats, but the pro-administration faction narrowly retained control of the chamber.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 3rd United States Congress, in 1792 and 1793.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Congress was broadly divided between a Pro-Administration faction supporting the policies of George Washington's administration and an Anti-Administration faction opposed to those policies.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Due to this, the Federalist Party (generally overlapping with the Pro-Administration faction) and the Democratic-Republican Party (generally overlapping with the Anti-Administration faction) were starting to emerge as the distinct political parties of the First Party System.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In this election, the Pro-Administration faction maintained control of the Senate, but lost its majority in the House.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, incumbent President George Washington was re-elected without any major opposition.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington had considered retirement, but was convinced to seek re-election for the purpose of national unity.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Though Washington went unchallenged, Governor George Clinton of New York sought to unseat John Adams as vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Adams received the second most electoral votes, and so was re-elected to office.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the House, 37 seats were added following the 1790 census.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction picked up several seats, narrowly taking the majority from the Pro-Administration faction.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Frederick Muhlenberg, who leaned closer to the Pro-Administration faction, was elected Speaker of the House.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Anti-Administration faction picked up one seat, but the Pro-Administration faction maintained a small majority.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Elections occurred in the middle of President George Washington's second term.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Members of the 4th United States Congress were chosen in this election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Tennessee was admitted as a state during the 4th Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] The election took place at the beginning of the First Party System, with the Democratic-Republican Party and Federalist Party emerging as political parties, succeeding the anti-administration faction and the pro-administration faction.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the House, the Democratic-Republicans picked up a small number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] However, Federalist Jonathan Dayton was elected Speaker of the House, defeating Frederick Muhlenberg, who had a less clear partisan affiliation.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Federalists picked up a moderate number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 5th United States Congress, in 1796 and 1797.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The election took place during the beginning stages of the First Party System, as the Federalist Party and the Democratic-Republican Party clashed over the states' rights, the financial policies of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton, and the recently ratified Jay Treaty.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The Federalists maintained control of the Senate, and won control of the House and the presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the first contested presidential election and the first presidential election in which parties played a major role, Federalist Vice President John Adams narrowly defeated Democratic-Republican former Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams won New England while Jefferson won the South, leaving the mid-Atlantic states to decide the election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] As the election took place prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, Jefferson, who finished with the second most electoral votes, succeeded Adams as vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Federalist former Governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina finished with the third most electoral votes, while Democratic-Republican Senator Aaron Burr of New York finished in fourth place.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] This election marked the only time in American history that members of two different political parties were elected as president and vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams's election made him the first member of a political party to be elected president, as George Washington had remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the House, Federalists won moderate gains, taking majority control of the chamber.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the Senate, Federalists picked up one seat, maintaining a commanding majority in the chamber.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1796–97 United States House of Representatives elections** took place in the various states between August 12, 1796 (in North Carolina), and October 15, 1797 (in Tennessee).
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 106 seats after Tennessee became the 16th U.S. state to join the union.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the 5th United States Congress was convened on May 15, 1797, at the proclamation of the new President of the United States, John Adams.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since Kentucky and Tennessee had not yet voted, they were unrepresented until the second session began on November 13, 1797.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Gains for the Federalist Party provided the president with a reliable majority in support of his policies.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Many of the Federalist pick-ups in Congress came from the former Middle Colonies (New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and Delaware).
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New England remained heavily Federalist, whereas the South and West favored Democratic-Republican candidates.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Federalist trade and infrastructure policies found widespread approval in the Mid-Atlantic states during this era.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the growth of cities in Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New York, government intervention in the interest of industrialization and mercantilism became more attractive to voting citizens in these areas.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] During this period, each state fixed its own date for a congressional general election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when a Congress convened.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 1st session of the 5th Congress ran May 15 – July 10, 1797, before the states of Kentucky and Tennessee had their elections, causing those states to be unrepresented in the 1st session.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by election date, then by district.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 4th Congress in 1796.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 5th Congress in 1797.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected its seven representatives at-large on a general ticket.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two of the four Democratic-Republicans were replaced by Federalists, bringing the Federalists from a 4–4 split to a 6–2 majority.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for election, necessitating additional trials in three districts.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In 1796, New Hampshire had a single at-large district with 4 seats.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each voter cast 4 votes and a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required to be elected.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since only three candidates received a majority, a run-off was held between the candidates in fourth and fifth place to fill the remaining seat.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island had an at-large district with two seats, each of which were elected separately.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to Vermont's law requiring a majority to secure a congressional seat, the 1st district required three ballots to choose a winner.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] The **1796–97 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1796 and 1797, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 1.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] They coincided with John Adams's election as President.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] The ruling Federalist Party gained one seat.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] After the August 2, 1796 admission of Tennessee.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] In these special elections, the winners were seated before March 4, 1797; ordered by election date.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1797; ordered by state.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] All of the elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] In these special elections, the winners were elected after the March 4, 1797 beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] John Eager Howard won election to fill the seat vacated by Richard Potts by an unknown number of votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] John Eager Howard won re-election over Richard Sprigg Jr. by an unknown number of votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] James Lloyd won election over William Winder by a margin of 1.12%, or 1 vote, for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Tennessee became a state June 1, 1796 and elected its new senators August 2, 1796.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] The term of the initially elected senator, Democratic-Republican William Cocke, ended March 3, 1797, and the Tennessee legislature failed to elect a senator for the new term.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] The governor of Tennessee, therefore, appointed Cocke to begin the term, pending a special election.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Cocke, however, lost that October 6, 1798 special election to Democratic-Republican Andrew Jackson.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Democratic-Republican William Blount was expelled July 8, 1797 for conspiracy with the Kingdom of Great Britain.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Democratic-Republican Joseph Anderson was elected September 26, 1797 to finish Blount's term.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Democratic-Republican Moses Robinson resigned October 15, 1796.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Federalist Isaac Tichenor was elected October 18, 1796, both to finish Robinson's term and to the new term that would begin March 4, 1797.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] However, Tichenor resigned just one year later, October 17, 1797, to become Governor of Vermont.
[src:1796-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-senate-elections] Federalist Nathaniel Chipman was then elected October 17, 1797, to finish the term.
